  "response_text": "The mean household risk attitude exhibits significant divergence among agents over time. Initially, risk attitudes cluster between -0.1 and 0.2 at step 0. From step 0 to 20, most agents demonstrate a rapid increase in risk attitude, with several reaching values between 0.5 and 0.8 by step 30. The highest values stabilize near 0.8 by step 50 and remain constant until step 100. In contrast, a subset of agents shows a decline in risk attitude after step 40. By step 60, the lowest risk attitudes drop to approximately -0.3, maintaining this level through step 100. Mid-range values fluctuate between 0.1 and 0.6 from step 40 onwards, reflecting heterogeneous behavioral adaptation among households."
}

